Hence commeth it that they withdraw the people from reading of the Scriptures, and that they hinder the tranſlating of them into the vulgar tongue. Hence commeth it, that they labour ſo much to caſt an aſperſion upon the Scriptures, and to make them to be ſuſpected by the people, as a dangerous booke; and that the reading thereof is the cauſe of hereſies. Hence came in Images, which ſerve to amaze, and to holde at gaze the eyes whilſt they blinde their underſtandings;

 and to afford them recreation, whilſt they withdraw and bereave the of inſtruction Hence came that heape of Ceremonies, which are ſhaddowes, which growe apace, and ſtretch out themſelves in length, when the night of ignorance is neere at hand. Hence came that implicit faith, which relyeth on the faith of another, and which beleeveth that which the Church of his countrey beleeveth, without ever knowing that which the Church ought to beleeve: and which ſerveth God by cuſtome, following the thronge, and involveing themſelves in the multitude. Hence came in the Liturgie in a ſtrange tongue, and not underſtood; as if the engliſh

 tongue were too baſe and triviall for divine ſervice. Hence came in the cuſtome of praying to God without knowing what they asked of him; as if they were affraid to underſtand themſelves. Hence came it to paſſe, that as in the publique reading of the Scriptures; God is a barbarian unto men, ſo alſo in publique prayers the Prieſt is a barbarian to the Aſſembly, and in the prayers of particulars, every one is a barbarian to himſelfe.
